solution: ```class Solution {
    private static final int MOD = 1_000_000_007;

    public int numMusicPlaylists(int n, int goal, int k) {
        long[][] dp = new long[goal + 1][n + 1];
        dp[0][0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i <= goal; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                dp[i][j] = (dp[i - 1][j - 1] * (n - j + 1)) % MOD;
                if (j > k) {
                    dp[i][j] = (dp[i][j] + dp[i - 1][j] * (j - k)) % MOD;
                }
            }
        }
        return (int) dp[goal][n];
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(goal * n)
space complexity: O(goal * n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses dynamic programming to count valid playlists. dp[i][j] tracks playlists of length i using j unique songs. Transitions either add a new song or reuse an old one while respecting the k-song gap. Space can be reduced to O(n) but kept for clarity.

